You can disable for just search engines using this filter, but I&#39;d advise **using it for all responses** as it&#39;s worse than just search engine unfriendly. It exposes the session ID which can be used for certain security exploits (&lt;a href=&quot;http://randomcoder.com/articles/jsessionid-considered-harmful&quot;&gt;more info&lt;/a&gt;).

**Tomcat 6 (pre 6.0.30)**

You can use the &lt;a href=&quot;http://tuckey.org/urlrewrite/&quot;&gt;tuckey rewrite filter&lt;/a&gt;.

&lt;a href=&quot;http://urlrewritefilter.googlecode.com/svn/trunk/src/doc/manual/3.2/guide.html&quot;&gt;Example config&lt;/a&gt; for Tuckey filter:

    &lt;outbound-rule encodefirst=&quot;true&quot;&gt;
      &lt;name&gt;Strip URL Session ID&#39;s&lt;/name&gt;
      &lt;from&gt;^(.*?)(?:\;jsessionid=[^\?#]*)?(\?[^#]*)?(#.*)?$&lt;/from&gt;
      &lt;to&gt;$1$2$3&lt;/to&gt;
    &lt;/outbound-rule&gt;

**Tomcat 6 (6.0.30 and onwards)**

You can use [disableURLRewriting][1] in the context configuration to disable this behaviour.

**Tomcat 7 and Tomcat 8**

From [Tomcat 7 onwards][2] you can add the following in the session config.

    &lt;session-config&gt;
        &lt;tracking-mode&gt;COOKIE&lt;/tracking-mode&gt;
    &lt;/session-config&gt;


